1 (o) "Standard report recipients" means the senate and house
2 appropriations subcommittees on state police, the senate and house
3 fiscal agencies, the senate and house policy offices, and the state
4 budget office.
5 Sec. 204. A department or agency shall use the internet to
6 fulfill the reporting requirements of this part and shall make each
7 report readily accessible to the public and conspicuously post each
8 required report in a single archivable location on the department's
9 or agency's Michigan.gov website not later than the due date
10 required for each report. In addition to placing all reports
11 required in the current fiscal year on the department's or agency's
12 website, the department or agency shall maintain on its website all
13 reports placed on the website from previous fiscal years, posted by
14 fiscal year, in the same single archivable location. The department
15 or agency shall also transmit all required reports for the current
16 fiscal year to the standard report recipients and any other
17 required recipients by email.
18 Sec. 205. To the extent permissible under section 261 of the
19 management and budget act, 1984 PA 431, MCL 18.1261, all of the
20 following apply to the expenditure of funds appropriated in part 1:
21 (a) The funds must not be used for the purchase of foreign
22 goods or services, or both, if competitively priced and of
23 comparable quality American goods or services, or both, are
24 available.
25 (b) Preference must be given to goods or services, or both,
26 manufactured or provided by Michigan businesses, if they are
27 competitively priced and of comparable quality.
28 (c) Preference must be given to goods or services, or both,
29 that are manufactured or provided by Michigan businesses owned and
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

13
1 operated by veterans, if they are competitively priced and of
2 comparable quality.
3 Sec. 206. The department shall not take disciplinary action
4 against an employee of the department for communicating with a
5 member of the legislature or legislative staff, unless the
6 communication is prohibited by law and the department is exercising
7 its authority as provided by law.
8 Sec. 207. Consistent with section 217 of the management and
9 budget act, 1984 PA 431, MCL 18.1217, each department and agency
10 receiving appropriations in part 1 shall prepare a report on out-
11 of-state travel expenses not later than January 1 of each year. The
12 report must list all travel by classified and unclassified
13 employees outside this state in the previous fiscal year that was
14 funded in whole or in part with funds appropriated in the
15 department's or agency's budget. The department or agency shall
16 submit the report to the standard report recipients and to the
17 senate and house appropriations committees. The report must include
18 all of the following information:
19 (a) The dates of each travel occurrence.
20 (b) The total transportation and related costs of each travel
21 occurrence and the proportion funded with state general
22 fund/general purpose revenues, state restricted revenues, federal
23 revenues, local revenues, and private revenues, including specific
24 sources of state restricted, federal, and other revenues.
25 Sec. 208. If the state administrative board, acting under
26 section 3 of 1921 PA 2, MCL 17.3, transfers funds from an amount
27 appropriated under part 1, the legislature may, by a concurrent
28 resolution adopted by a majority of the members elected to and
29 serving in each house, intertransfer funds within part 1 for the
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

