3 Sec. 212. Not later than 14 days after the release of the
4 executive budget recommendation, the department shall cooperate
5 with the state budget office to provide an annual report on
6 estimated state restricted fund balances, state restricted fund
7 projected revenues, and state restricted fund expenditures for the
8 previous 2 fiscal years. The report must be submitted to the
9 standard report recipients and to the chairpersons of the senate
10 and house appropriations committees.
11 Sec. 213. (1) Funds appropriated in part 1 must not be used to
12 restrict or impede a marginalized community's access to government
13 resources, programs, or facilities.
14 (2) From the funds appropriated in part 1, local governments
15 shall report any action or policy that attempts to restrict or
16 interfere with the duties of a local health officer.
17 Sec. 214. To the extent permissible under the management and
18 budget act, 1984 PA 431, MCL 18.1101 to 18.1594, the director of
19 each department or agency receiving appropriations in part 1 shall
20 take all reasonable steps to ensure that geographically
21 disadvantaged business enterprises compete for and perform
22 contracts to provide services or supplies, or both. The director
23 shall strongly encourage firms with which the department contracts
24 to subcontract with geographically disadvantaged business
25 enterprises for services or supplies, or both. As used in this
26 section, "geographically disadvantaged business enterprises" means
27 that term as defined in Executive Directive No. 2023-01.
28 Sec. 215. (1) The department shall maximize utilization of its
29 in-person state workforce. The department shall prioritize
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

16
1 occupancy utilization of office space for each division within the
2 department. Employees with job responsibilities that require the
3 employees to serve in their capacities outside of an office shall
4 be monitored each pay period to ensure all work hours reported on
5 the timesheet were actually worked.
6 (2) The department shall comply with requirements set forth by
7 the office of the state employer on in-person work and utilization
8 and occupancy rates of state buildings to ensure in-person work is
9 optimized and occupancy rates are 80% or higher, subject to market
10 conditions.
11 (3) The department shall adhere to civil service rules and
12 regulations that state the standard biweekly work period for a
13 full-time employee in the classified service of this state is the
14 equivalent of 80.0 hours of work. The department shall establish
15 policies and processes to ensure all employees are working their
16 jobs during agreed-upon business hours.
17 Sec. 216. On a quarterly basis, the department or agency
18 receiving appropriations in part 1 shall report on the number of
19 full-time equated positions in pay status by civil service
20 classification, including a comparison by line item of the number
21 of full-time equated positions authorized from funds appropriated
22 in part 1 to the actual number of full-time equated positions
23 employed by the department at the end of the reporting period. The
24 report must be submitted to the standard report recipients and to
25 the senate and house appropriations committees.
26 Sec. 218. A department or agency that receives an
27 appropriation under this part or part 1 must provide an annual
28 report to the standard report recipients detailing federal policy
29 changes that do, or are expected to do, any of the following:
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

17
1 (a) Affect the operations of the department, including
2 reductions in federal revenue. For federal revenue reductions, the
3 annual report must detail the impact on the department or agency
4 and residents of this state, including, but not limited to, all of
5 the following information:
6 (i) The amount of additional state revenue required to replace
7 the lost federal revenue.
8 (ii) The services the department or agency will have to reduce
9 or eliminate due to the lost revenue.
10 (iii) The anticipated fiscal impact on residents of this state.
11 (b) Affect an industry, community, population, or other group
12 regulated or served by, or that otherwise engages with, the
13 department or agency.
14 (c) Create a regulatory gap that could negatively impact the
15 public.
16 (d) Increase the department's or agency's costs.
17 (e) Reduce or eliminate a program that provides services to
18 residents of this state.
19 Sec. 219. The department shall receive and retain copies of
20 all reports funded from appropriations in part 1. The department
21 shall follow federal and state law and guidelines for short-term
22 and long-term retention of records. The department may
23 electronically retain copies of reports unless otherwise required
24 by federal and state guidelines.
25 Sec. 220. Not later than April 1, the department shall report
26 on each specific policy change made to implement a public act
27 affecting the department that took effect during the previous
28 calendar year. The report must include reference to the public act
29 that necessitates the policy change. The department shall submit
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

