27 sessions to enhance safe response in the event of natural or
28 manmade incidents, emergencies, or disasters.
29 (7) In addition to the funds appropriated in part 1, there is
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

42
1 appropriated from the disaster and emergency contingency fund an
2 amount necessary to cover costs related to any disaster or
3 emergency as defined in the emergency management act, 1976 PA 390,
4 MCL 30.401 to 30.421. Funds must be expended as provided under
5 sections 18 and 19 of the emergency management act, 1976 PA 390,
6 MCL 30.418 and 30.419, and R 30.51 to R 30.61 of the Michigan
7 Administrative Code.
8 (8) If, in a particular month, expenditures are made from the
9 disaster and emergency contingency fund, the department shall
10 submit a report for that month to the senate and house fiscal
11 agencies detailing the purpose of the expenditures. The monthly
12 report required under this subsection must be submitted within 30
13 days after the end of the month during which funds from the
14 disaster and emergency contingency fund were expended.
15 (9) The department shall track and report on a biannual basis,
16 as provided in section 228 of this part, the status of the
17 department's assessment of critical infrastructure vulnerabilities,
18 including the protection status of critical infrastructure items
19 identified by the assessment. The department is not required to
20 report any information that could compromise the security of any
21 critical infrastructure.
22 (10) Revenue collected by the department under this section
23 for the emergency management and homeland security training center
24 that is unexpended and unencumbered at the end of the fiscal year
25 must not lapse to the general fund, but must be carried forward
26 into the subsequent fiscal year.
27 Sec. 705. The department shall provide for the planning,
28 administration, and implementation of highway traffic safety
29 programs to save lives and reduce injuries on roads in this state,
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

43
1 in partnership with other public and private organizations.
2 Sec. 706. (1) Funds appropriated in part 1 for the secondary
3 road patrol program must be used to provide grants to sheriffs
4 under the secondary road patrol program described under section 76
5 of 1846 RS 14, MCL 51.76.
6 (2) The sheriffs' duties under the secondary road patrol
7 program, as outlined in section 76(2) of 1846 RS 14, MCL 51.76, are
8 to do all of the following:
9 (a) Patrol and monitor traffic violations.
10 (b) Enforce the criminal laws of this state, violations of
11 which are observed by or brought to the attention of the sheriff's
12 department while patrolling and monitoring secondary roads.
13 (c) Investigate accidents involving motor vehicles.
14 (d) Provide emergency assistance to persons on or near a
15 highway or road the sheriff is patrolling and monitoring.
16 Sec. 707. The department shall serve as an active liaison
17 between the department of technology, management, and budget and
18 state, local, regional, and federal public safety agencies on
19 matters pertaining to the Michigan public safety communications
20 system and shall report user issues to the department of
21 technology, management, and budget.
22
23 ONE-TIME APPROPRIATIONS
24 Sec. 801. (1) The general fund/general purpose funds
25 appropriated in part 1 for the disaster and emergency contingency
26 fund must be deposited into the disaster and emergency contingency
27 fund created in section 18 of the emergency management act, 1976 PA
28 390, MCL 30.418.
29 (2) Due to a significant increase in climate-related
STM S06116'26 (S-1) b0u6xa

44
1 emergencies and disaster events, the existing $10,000,000.00
2 statutory cap and distribution guidelines in section 18 of the
3 emergency management act, 1976 PA 390, MCL 30.418, are not
4 sufficient. It is the intent of the legislature to complete passage
5 of Senate Bill No. 109 of 2025 and increase funding to meet the
6 needs of residents and communities impacted by emergencies or
7 disaster events.
